      <p>The <strong>MX Anywhere 3S</strong> is our runner-up and the right choice for travelers. It uses the same sensor and the same MagSpeed scroll wheel, but in a smaller, lighter body that fits in a laptop pocket. The trade-off is ergonomics — the smaller shape fatigues larger hands after about four hours. If you work at a desk most of the time, spend the extra $20 on the MX Master 3S. If you live out of a backpack, the Anywhere 3S is the better pick.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Logitech M720 Triathlon</strong> is the budget champion. At $40 it has a hyper-fast scroll wheel (mechanical, not MagSpeed), three-device pairing, and a comfortable shape that suits most hand sizes. It is not as precise, the scroll wheel does not free-spin as smoothly, and the build quality feels cheaper. But for the price it is remarkable. If you are buying mice for an entire team, this is the smart pick.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Microsoft Surface Precision Mouse</strong> is the only mouse here that competes on build quality, with a solid metal scroll wheel and a premium feel. But it lacks Flow, the scroll wheel does not free-spin, and the battery only lasts 30 days. For most people it is not worth the trade-off.</p>

      <p>Pair any of these with the <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-keys-s-review/">Logitech MX Keys S</a> keyboard for a matching multi-device setup, or check our <a href="/reviews/keychron-k8-review/">Keychron K8 review</a> if you prefer mechanical feel.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the MX Master 3S at full price if you spend more than four hours a day at a computer and switch between two or three devices. The Flow feature alone justifies the price for multi-machine workers. If you are a single-machine user who mainly writes and browses, the $40 M720 covers 80% of what the MX Master 3S does — skip the upgrade.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Logitech runs promotions around Prime Day and Black Friday where the MX Master 3S drops to $69 to $79. We have seen it as low as $59 during clearance events. Set a price alert if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Skip the MX Master 3 (without the S) unless it is heavily discounted. The older version lacks quiet clicks, has a weaker sensor, and struggles on glass. Paying $20 less for meaningfully worse tracking is not a good deal.</p>

      <p>Get a desk pad. A good mouse deserves a consistent surface, and a large pad also protects your desk and unifies the look of your setup. We recommend one in our <a href="/reviews/best-desk-pad-large/">large desk pad guide</a>. If your laptop screen sits too low, pair the mouse with a <a href="/reviews/best-laptop-stand-desk/">laptop stand</a> to fix your neck posture at the same time.</p>

      <p>Avoid no-name brands on Amazon. Many look identical to the MX Master 3S at a quarter of the price, but the sensors skip, the scroll wheels break within months, and the batteries degrade fast. Stick with Logitech, Microsoft, Razer, or Keychron.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
